<Author>SorchaN
<Content>Nice hotel, good location, friendly staff I left it very late to book a hotel for my trip to Boston, so most of them were either full or way beyond my price range. I was getting anxious, but with only a few days to go I booked the Holiday Inn at Beacon Hill through Hotwire. When I arrived the desk staff were helpful and friendly. The room was clean and quite large, with two queen (I think) beds and an enormous window that went all the way from floor to ceiling, which meant the room was nice and bright during the daytime. (There were blackout curtains for guests who like it dark at night.) There was the usual city noise - car horns and sirens - from time to time, but it wasn't especially loud. The housekeeping staff are efficient and thorough, and were particularly good about my jet-lagged inability to get up and out before late morning. I think one morning the housekeeping staff came in a couple of times, saw me sleeping and went quietly away without disturbing me, and yet still came back later, once I'd gone out, to bring clean towels and stuff like that. (There is a card you can put on the door to request privacy, if you happen to think of it before you go to bed; I hadn't done that because I had very good intentions about getting up early every morning. Ha!)There are laptop points in all the rooms, but I don't have my own laptop so I was glad to be able to check my email in the small business center on the second floor, in which there are two PCs. I never had to wait long to use one. There's a printer in there too, but if you want to fax anything you need to go to the front desk.You can make direct dial international calls from the phones in the room, which is easier than having to use a credit card. However, it's pretty expensive! I think it's about $10 for the first minute, and then about $1 a minute after that, depending where you're calling. If you plan to make long distance or international calls, you might want to ask the front desk about the rates first. Hotel phones are always expensive, of course.There is also a guest laundry with two washers and two dryers on the second floor, which I liked because I was able to wash all my clothes before leaving, and they're always so much easier to pack when they're clean! (Small box of laundry powder from the front desk: $1.) One slight problem was that whenever both washers were being used the room flooded. There is a rather bizarre quick-fix plumbing device consisting of a tall pipe that leads nowhere, which might be able to deal with the water pressure of one draining washer, but which simply pours water all over the room when both are draining at the same time. Not a huge problem, but a bit odd.And there's a fitness room, also on the second floor, with treadmills and exercise bikes. I went once, but was too busy over the next few days to go again! It's nice to have access to something like that, especially when it's too cold to go for a long walk outdoors. There is an outdoor pool which was closed when I was there (in November) but would probably be great in the summertime.A couple of floors of the hotel are used as residences for students at a nearby college, but the students I encountered (usually in the laundry or the business center) were polite and friendly. They also didn't generate the kind of noise that people might expect from students: I didn't hear any loud music or partying while I was there. Also on the second floor of the hotel, just beyond the laundry, is a back door which leads outdoors to a CVS (pharmacy or chemist, depending where you're from) and a big whole food store that sells everything from scented candles to fresh fruit; from freshly made pizza to interesting cheeses. If you go in hungry you'll come out poor! Or maybe you're less easily tempted than I am.As you might expect in a major city, there are restaurants nearby, liquor stores, general stores and so on. If you want other kinds of shopping (shoes, clothes) it's easy enough to walk downtown or you can take the T. I'm not a big fan of shopping, but apparently there are places in the Back Bay neighborhood where designer shopping can be done.The T is very easy to get to: the nearest station is probably Bowdoin on the blue line, but it's closed evenings and weekends. I found it easier to get the T from Charles MGH (red line) which is about four minutes' walk from the Holiday Inn (and I'm not a fast walker). Trains come every couple of minutes, it's quick and easy to get almost anywhere, and it's pretty inexpensive: I got a Charlie ticket for a week, which was only $15. (it's called a Charlie ticket because of the song about Charlie and the MTA, which you have to listen to if you're going to Boston - the Kingston Trio sang it, among others).There is a restaurant attached to the hotel. It's a separate business, but you can get breakfast or other meals there. It's also a bar. I didn't go into it, so I can't review it except to say it's handy. I think, though, if I could change one thing about this hotel, it would be about breakfast. It's nice to have a restaurant pretty much on-site, but I have some strong views about breakfast, one of which is that it shouldn't cost nearly as much as a weekly ticket on the subway. Call me unreasonable if you want. So instead of going for breakfast at the restaurant I went out the back door every morning, across to the whole food store, and bought bananas and grapes for breakfast. Checkout is at noon, and my flight wasn't leaving until evening, so I asked if I could leave my luggage for a few hours. That was just fine: it was kept in a locked room and I was given a receipt for collecting it. So I was able to go out for a while without having to schlep my bags around. A taxi to or from the airport is just under $25, which I thought was good value. But it's also possible to get to the airport by taking the T, which is cheaper of course. Either the blue line or the silver line will get you to the airport.I enjoyed my stay at the Holiday Inn at Beacon Hill and would quite happily go back there on any future trips to Boston. 
